<HEADLINE>
<P>
MARKETING / BRUCE HOROVITZ: REBIRTH OF BASEBALL; THE NATIONAL PASTIME HAS 
REINVENTED ITSELF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRUCE HOROVITZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With or without Michael Jordan on its 1994 roster, Major League Baseball 
appears to be making a magnificent off-the-field comeback. Behind it all: 
shrewd marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 Just one year ago, baseball was saddled with more image problems than Tonya 
Harding. TV viewership was in the tank. Attendance had been flat for four 
years. Advertisers were grumbling. Fans were fed up with greedy owners, crybaby 
players and high ticket prices. Media criticism was relentless. Baseball became 
the Rodney Dangerfield of professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
 Yet fans flocked to ballparks in record numbers last year -- a record that 
would have been achieved even without the two expansion teams that joined the 
National League. Now, with opening day less than three weeks away, it appears 
to be OK again to admit to liking baseball. 
</P>
<P>
 This image reversal -- while far from complete -- is due in large part to 
clever marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 "Baseball is making a major-league comeback," said Alan Friedman, editor of 
Team Marketing Report in Chicago. "The sport is finally playing up its strong 
points." 
</P>
<P>
 The turnaround began last year with an announced overhaul of baseball's 
playoff structure -- which is expected to pump some pizazz into the game. It 
continued this winter with the formation of the Baseball Network, a powerful 
marketing group that will give fans more of what they want most: home teams on 
TV. 
</P>
<P>
 Marketers are also catching on to the emergence of several young superstars 
who are showing up in national ads -- and even in computer games. And it is no 
accident that two marquee athletes -- Michael Jordan and Bo Jackson -- are 
wearing baseball jerseys this spring. 
</P>
<P>
 "Baseball has finally gotten ahead of the curve," said Michael Trager, 
executive vice president of sales and marketing for the New York-based Baseball 
Network. The group is a joint venture of Major League Baseball and ABC and NBC, 
the two networks that will share baseball's national TV time this year. 
</P>
<P>
 Its first move was to scrap baseball's Saturday afternoon Game of the Week. 
Reason: Viewership has declined 35% since 1986, Trager said. In its place will 
be weekly evening broadcasts of local or regional teams on the networks. 
"That's what fans want," Trager said. 
</P>
<P>
 Some off-the-field changes are expected to immediately make baseball a more 
marketable commodity in 1994. A new league alignment -- with fewer teams in 
each division -- means each team has a better shot at making the playoffs. And 
a revised playoff structure also means more teams will participate in 
post-season play this year. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Instead of advertising baseball by showing fans cheering in the stands, the 
networks are calling upon baseball's stars to promote the '94 season. Some of 
these young stars are finally picking up endorsement contracts as well. 
</P>
<P>
 Barry Bonds, the reclusive slugger for the San Francisco Giants, is in TV 
spots for Wilson and Nike. Ken Griffey Jr., the Seattle Mariners star, has 
linked up with Nike and Kellogg. And a Nintendo computer baseball game bearing 
Griffey's name hits the market next week. Chicago White Sox batting star Frank 
Thomas is featured in a Reebok TV spot. 
</P>
<P>
 The Baseball Network is expected to soon announce a handful of sponsors that 
will buy ad time during the games and forge promotional tie-ins. Texaco will 
sponsor the 1994 All-Star Game balloting. In fact, more ballots are expected to 
be filled out at Texaco gas stations this year than in all 28 baseball 
stadiums, said Tom Matthews, president of Texaco Refining & Marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, former NBA superstar Jordan -- whose minor league performance has 
been, at best, disappointing -- has still created a media frenzy while trying 
to catch on with the White Sox. And Jackson -- whose hip surgery two years ago 
may have shortened his baseball career -- is a sure bet to fill some seats at 
Anaheim Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
 Yet both teams have been careful about how they promote these superstars to 
local fans. Neither player is expected to be a starter this year -- and Jordan 
may not even make the team. 
</P>
<P>
 "These guys are shedding light on the hunger there is for a larger-than-life 
baseball hero," said Brian Murphy, editor of the Westport, Conn.-based Sports 
Marketing Letter. "Baseball doesn't need to retool its marketing; all baseball 
needs is one or two heroes." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 But for the time being, at least, Angel fans won't see much of Jackson in ads. 
</P>
<P>
 "As a marketing person, you salivate over the fact that you have a Bo Jackson 
in camp. He just walks on the field and everyone cheers," said Joseph Schrier, 
vice president of marketing for the Angels. "But we don't want to mislead fans 
or embarrass anybody by featuring him in our advertising. We have to first make 
sure that he makes the team." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Jackson did appear in a preseason newspaper ad in Tempe, Ariz., which 
helped fill the spring training ballpark. The ad showed Jackson in an Angel 
uniform under the headline "Un-Bo-lievable." 
</P>
<P>
 An even touchier marketing dilemma is taking place in Chicago. Officials there 
are trying to decide what credible role -- if any -- White Sox wanna-be Jordan 
can play in the team's marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 Clearly, just allowing Jordan to try out for the team has been a marketing 
windfall. 
</P>
<P>
 The White Sox found a way to get Jordan's mug into one ad. A TV spot shows him 
reminiscing about how the Chicago Bulls won pro basketball's World Championship 
just one season after they first made the playoffs. The spot implies that this 
will be the White Sox's big year too. 
</P>
<P>
 But the ad clearly portrays Jordan as a basketball star -- not a baseball 
player. And the real star of the TV spot is Frank Thomas, the White Sox's 
hitting star, who is seen smirking at the end of the ad. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our responsibility from the marketing side is to stick with the guys who got 
us here," said Rob Gallas, White Sox senior vice president of marketing. "Even 
if Jordan makes the team, it will be as the 28th man. We don't want to market 
Michael Jordan as a novelty act." 
</P>
<P>
 But Nike may be doing just that. The firm is selling T-shirts and baseball 
caps that promote Jordan as a baseball player. One shirt shows Jordan -- bat in 
hand -- under the headline "The Great American Pastime Just Got Greater." 
</P>
<P>
 "There's a demand out in the marketplace for Michael Jordan baseball stuff," 
said Keith Peters, a Nike spokesman, "even if his baseball career only lasts a 
few months." Briefly . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles agency GBF/Ayer has picked up the $1.4-million ad business for 
the Avery Division of Pasadena-based Avery Dennison, an office products maker. 
. . . Los Angeles-based Fox Broadcasting Co. is talking to local ad agencies 
about a campaign to help it promote broadcasts of National Football League 
games. . . . Central California Advertising Connection, an ad sales company 
specializing in cable TV and radio, has opened in Los Angeles. . . . To help 
raise money for the Minority Advertising Training Program, the Western States 
Advertising Agencies Assn. will host a private screening of Ron Howard's film 
"The Paper" at 7:30 tonight at Cineplex Odeon in Universal City. Gimmicks to 
Fill Seats 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles Dodgers and California Angels have devised new marketing 
gimmicks to fill seats during the '94 baseball season. Here are some of the 
newer or more unusual efforts: 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Dodgers: 
</P>
<P>
 * Ad campaign promoting Dodgers as "the best buy in town." 
</P>
<P>
 * Ads promoting the team's "back-to-back" rookies of the year. 
</P>
<P>
 * Minority marketing campaigns aimed at Latinos, Japanese, Koreans and 
Filipinos. 
</P>
<P>
 * Baseball clinics with Dodger players and various youth groups. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Photo Ball Night" at Dodger Stadium featuring baseballs with photos of top 
rookies. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Dodger Dog Night" featuring free hot dogs for every fan. 
</P>
<P>
 * Special Dodger Stadium clothing line to be sold only at Dodger Stadium. 
California Angels: 
</P>
<P>
 * New Angels "mascots" leading cheers in stands and on the field. 
</P>
<P>
 * New Angels "halo cheer" to be introduced following Angel home runs. 
</P>
<P>
 * More quizzes and games on scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
 * Two-for-one ticket promotions. 
</P>
<P>
 * New slogan: "Angels Baseball: You Gotta Love It." 
</P>
<P>
 * "Calculator Night," with 20,000 calculators given away. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Umbrella Night," with 20,000 umbrellas given away. 
</P>
<P>
 Sources: Barry Stockhamer, VP Marketing, Los Angeles Dodgers; Joseph Schrier, 
VP Marketing, California Angels. Baseball's Back 
</P>
<P>
 Despite all of its image problems, Major League Baseball attendance climbed 
sharply last year. The two new expansion teams--which attracted nearly 7.5 
million fans--accounted for a little over half the gain. 
</P>
<P>
 Total 1993 attendance: 70.2 million 
</P>
<P>
 Source: Major League Baseball 
</P>
</TEXT>
