<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: BRUSSELS; EU MEETS ON EXPANSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The European Union's 12 foreign ministers meet here today to try to complete 
negotiations with Norway on the terms of its entry to the union. The plan is to 
present the Norwegian entry application to the European Parliament on 
Wednesday, together with those of Austria, Finland and Sweden, whose terms of 
entry have already been agreed on. 
</P>
<P>
 Proving even tougher to resolve than the entry talks themselves is the issue 
of what would constitute a so-called "blocking minority" in union voting. 
Britain and Spain are insisting on the present formula by which two big nations 
and one small one can effectively combine to block new initiatives. The others 
insist that as the union grows, so too must the blocking minority. 
</P>
<P>
 Because the terms of entry must be approved by the European Parliament and 
subjected to referendums in all four countries, both issues must be resolved 
this week if the enlargement is to take effect as scheduled next Jan. 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
