<P>
THE STYLE FILES: THE PLACES; TURF WEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHELE SEIPP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Los Angeles may be a melting pot, but it's definitely divided itself into 
fashion turfs and tribes.At the Crenshaw District's Fifth Street Dick's, high 
stylists in ethnic wear and soft leather bob their heads to the sounds of cool 
jazz and cappuccino machines. Mrs. Gooch's in Beverly Hills houses expensively 
attired health-concious types, incognito in dark glasses. Who wants to be 
recognized while considering the fiber content in yam chips? Venice's Gold's 
Gym habitues take their passion to gargantuan extremes -- extra-loose, 
parachute-like clothes are the only answer for bulging biceps, quads and lats. 
Downtown, at the Museum of Contemporary Art, ultra-serious, back-pack-toting 
art students in fringed jackets and leggings ponder the work of Roy 
Lichtenstein. MICHELE SEIPP 
</P>
